article.headline: San Diego State 83, San Diego 63
article.story: SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The annual crosstown game between San Diego and San Diego State looked like a rivalry for about five minutes. Then it was San Diego State all the way. Brandon Heath scored 26 points and Chris Manker had 22 to lead the Aztecs to an 83-63 win over the Toreros on Wednesday night, their third straight in the series. "I didn't think it was going to be like this," SDSU's Marcus Slaughter said. "Our defense was tremendous today. We made them turn the ball over and we made them do things they didn't want to do." The previous four games in this series were decided by six points or fewer. San Diego State was behind 14-8 with 14:23 left in the first half, then went on a 9-0 run and never trailed again. "We definitely played our best game tonight," Manker said. "This was really a complete team win." Manker, a 7-footer, scored San Diego State's first nine points of the second half to give the Aztecs a 47-32 lead. He hit two straight 3-pointers and converted a 3-point play. Manker is getting more playing time because Chris Walton is out with hip and groin injuries. "He's getting to play and shoot the ball," San Diego State coach Steve Fisher said. "It's tough to shoot the ball when you're sitting on the bench." San Diego State (3-1), coming off an 86-51 win over Division II UC San Diego, matched its best start in 20 seasons. The Toreros fell to 2-3. It was San Diego State's biggest winning margin in the series since an 84-61 win in 1975. "By far the best defensive effort we've had for an extended period of time," Fisher said. San Diego State outrebounded the Toreros 38-24 and held San Diego to 48.4 percent shooting. "State did a great job of transition and rebounding," San Diego coach Brad Holland said. "They got too many easy baskets and second-chance points for us to be in the game." San Diego's leading scorer, forward Brandon Gay, sustained a mild concussion late in the first half and didn't return. He had just five points at the time, 15 short of his average. Heath limped off the court after ending up in a heap after making a layup with 9:14 left for a 68-54, but came back in a few minutes later. John Sharper had 13 points for San Diego State while Slaughter had 12 points and 12 rebounds. Brett Melton led the Toreros with 16 points, followed by Brice Vounang with 15 and Nick Lewis 11. The Aztecs closed the first half with three 3-pointers, two by Sharper, to take a 38-27 lead.
